practices at some of America's most prestigious firms, Lauren Rivera shows how, at every step of the hiring process, the ways that employers define and evaluate merit are strongly skewed to favor job applicants from economically privileged backgrounds. She reveals how decision makers draw from ideas about talent-what it is, what best signals it, and who does (and does not) have it-that are deeply rooted in social class. Displaying the "right stuff" that elite employers are looking for entails considerable amounts of economic, social, and cultural resources on the part of the applicants and their parents.Challenging our most cherished beliefs about college as a great equalizer and the job market as a level playing field, Pedigree exposes the class biases built into American notions about the best and the brightest, and shows how social status plays a significant role in determining who reaches the top of the economic ladder.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCollege graduatesxEmploymentzUnited States. 0aEconomicsxSociological aspects. 0aElite (Social sciences)zUnited States. 0aEmployee selectionzUnited States. 0aEmployment (Economic theory)xSocial aspects. 0aUpper classxEmploymentzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Classes & Economic Disparity.2bisacsh1 aRivera, Lauren A.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400880744zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400880744423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400880744.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK